FIFA Disciplinary Committee's Unreasonable "Decision" Refuted 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- Cheyuk Sinmun (sports newspaper) of the DPRK Friday in a commentary termed the "decision" taken by the Disciplinary Committee of the FIFA against the behaviors of Korean spectators an unreasonable one.
 The commentary says:
  Recently the committee took a disciplinary step against behaviors of spectators after the matches between the DPRK team and the Bahraini team and between the DPRK team and the Iranian team. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The "decision" calls for holding the match between the DPRK team and the Japanese team in a stadium without spectators in a third country, instead of having it in Pyongyang on June 8 as scheduled, and imposing a fine upon the DPRK team. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The disciplinary measure taken by the FIFA Disciplinary Committee against the behaviors of spectators after painting them as a "disturbance" and considering it as an established fact is lashing the Korean people into great fury because they deem the national dignity as their life and soul. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It was a prejudice that the FIFA Disciplinary Committee "branded" the just actions of spectators as a "disturbance" or "commotion". The DPRK Football Association in a statement of its spokesman protested against the unreasonable behavior of the referees, sent video tapes on which the unfair refereeing is recorded to the FIFA Disciplinary Committee and its members received and watched them. And the committee exceptionally invited a DPRK delegation to hear from it the principled request for dealing with the unreasonable behavior of the referees. The committee, however, turned it down and adopted such a harsh "decision" against the DPRK team. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The soccer history does not record such awfully unfair refereeing as what happened during the matches held here. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If the FIFA Disciplinary Committee allows such partial refereeing to go on, this will cast a darker shadow on the development of the world soccer in the future. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The committee should sternly punish those who partially refereed the matches and apply sanctions against them. 
 The committee has left a blot on its history by taking such an unjust "decision" against the DPRK team which took just actions while respecting rules concerning discipline instituted by the FIFA. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What should not be overlooked is that the committee could not properly fulfill its duty because it more attentively listened to an "advice" made by Japan. This is the comment of the world public. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 No sooner had the committee made the unreasonable decision than Japan proposed to have Malaysia as the venue of match before any other country.  It is the ulterior motive of Japan to trounce the DPRK team by creating a favorable environment for it come what may. Japan is running so wild to achieve its aim, unaware that it has become a laughing-stock of the world. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If it is true that the dignified FIFA Disciplinary Committee accepted Japan's "advice," it would be an irretrievable historic mistake committed by it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is our hope that the FIFA Disciplinary Committee will reexamine the issues related to the above-mentioned case and make a wise judgment for the sake of its authority, the development of football and the future of the FIFA. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 We will closely follow the future attitude of the FIFA Disciplinary Committee.

Anniversary of DPRK-Thai Diplomatic Ties Marked 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- A meeting was held at the Chollima House of Culture Thursday to mark the 30th anniversary of the opening of diplomatic relations between the DPRK and Thailand.
 Present were Chairman Kang Chol Su and members of the Korea-Thailand Friendship Association and working people in the city. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chairman made a speech there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After the meeting participants went round photographs introducing Thailand.

Events Held to Mark Russia's Day of War Victory 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- The Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries and the DPRK-Russia Friendship Association arranged a photo exhibition and a film show at the Chollima House of Culture Thursday
to mark the 60th anniversary of the victory of Russia in the Great Patriotic War.
 Present on invitation were Russian Ambassador to the DPRK Andrei Karlov and embassy officials. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand were Mun Jae Chol, acting chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, Hong Son Ok, vice-chairperson of the committee and chairperson of the association, officials concerned and working people in the city. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants went round photos showing the heroic struggle waged by the army and people of Russia against the armed invasion by the fascist German aggressors before watching a feature film "In the Fourth Year of the War".

April Fetes of DPRK Celebrated in 100 Odd Countries 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- Grand functions were held in at least 100 countries on the occasions of the Day of the Sun, the 12th anniversary of leader Kim Jong Il's election as chairman of the DPRK National Defence Commission and the birthday of the Korean People's Army.
 Floral baskets were presented to President Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il by heads of state and government including the king of Cambodia, the Guinean president and the chief of the Palestinian National Authority, and political party leaders, public figures as well as political parties and organizations of different countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Il Sung's work "For a Free and Peaceful New World" was bought out in booklet by the Cantaclara Publishing House of Venezuela and Kim Jong Il's work "Let Us Carry Out the Great Leader Comrade Kim Il Sung's Instructions for National Reunification" by the Mongolian Mt. Paektu Association. The books "A Legendary Great Man" and "Great Succession" saw the light in Russia &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
and the book "Leader Possessed of Peculiar Political Ability" was published by the Group of Dialectical Materialists of Italy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Rojas City government in Ecuador held a special plenary session and registered Kim Il Sung, Kim Jong Il and anti-Japanese war hero Kim Jong Suk as honorary citizens and decided to present the key of the city to Kim Jong Il on the occasion of the Day of the Sun. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Nepal Journalist Association registered Kim Jong Il as an honorary special member of the association and presented its certificate to him. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 More than 400 colorful functions such as meetings, seminars, lectures, round-table talks and art performances took place in over 100 countries including China, Russia, Cuba, India, Nigeria, Tanzania, France, Mexico and Peru with the participation of senior government, military and public officials.

Total Cancellation of "5029" War Scenario Demanded 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) --  Recently the U.S. and the south Korean authorities concerned held a huddle over the issue of renaming "OPLAN 5029",
a very dangerous scenario of war against the north allegedly aimed at coping with a "contingency" to be created there, the "Notion Plan 5029".
 In this regard, a spokesman for the Committee for the Peaceful Reunification of the Fatherland issued a statement on Friday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The "Notion Plan 5029" is nothing different from "OPLAN 5029" in essence as both are anti-north war scenarios presupposing a military intervention in case of an emergency, the statement noted, and continued: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The mere change of the name of a scenario would never reduce its aggressive and dangerous nature. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 By origin, the "OPLAN 5029" is intolerable as its appearance and existence is a total negation of the north and a grave challenge to it. Therefore, it should be nullified unconditionally and totally. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A "contingency" is unthinkable in the DPRK society where all the servicepersons and people are single-mindedly united. It is like crying for the moon to expect this to happen. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They will never allow those who move to destroy the dignified system in the DPRK but mete out a deserved punishment to them, the statement warned.

Child Prodigies Produced by Kyongsang Kindergarten
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 6 (KCNA) -- Kyongsang Kindergarten in  Central District of Pyongyang, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, has brought up one more prodigy.
 Kim So Yon, who graduated from the kindergarten this year, is now studying at Pyongyang School of Arts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Already at the age of 3 she was prominent in her quick observation and understanding of things and phenomena and in musical sense and application. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For two years after she started taking piano lessons at the kindergarten at the age of five, she wrote and composed more than 100 songs including "Footsteps of the People's Army" and "Good, Indeed, Is Our Kindergarten." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
They are admired by even music experts. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kyongsang Kindergarten is famous for having produced many prodigies with good artistic talents. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kindergarteners there have made by themselves many teaching materials including books "How to Play Piano for Children" and "Sight Reading for Children" and visual aids and furnishing needed to develop the intelligence of the children. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They have worked out daily program run through with songs and dances, properly combining it with physical training and intelligence-developing games. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They have also directed deep attention to the early musical education. As a result, they have trained over 1,000 artistic talents over the last two decades. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Director of the kindergarten Kim Chun Sil told KCNA that such achievements could be made thanks to the excellent system of nursing and educating the children as the "king" of the country and to the sincere efforts of the kindergarteners to discharge their responsibility and duty.

